Choices:  A: radio shack B: substation C: cabinet D: television E: desk<n>Output:		C<n><n><n>### Solution:<n><n>```Java<n><n>  import java.io.*;<n>    input = readLine();<n>    string = input.split(",\\s*");<n>    for (i = 0; i < string.length; ++i)<n>    {<n>        str = string[i];<n>        c = str.charAt(str.length()-1);<n>        if (c == 'a')<n>            string.insert(string.insert(string.length()-1, "B"), i, "a");<n>        else<n>            string.insert(-1, "a", "B");<n>    }<n>    string.reverse();<n>    String s = "";<n>    for (i=0; i< string.length; ++ i)<n>    {<n>    s += string[i].charAt(0);<n>    }<n>    for (int i = 0 ; i<s.length(); ++i)<n>    s[i]='c';<n><n>    //String s = string[0].charAt(0)+string[1].charAt(0) + string[2].charAt(0).toString();<n>    for (int k=0;k<s.length();k++)<n>    s[k]='d';<n>    System.out.println(s);<n>}<n><n>```<n>![PNG](/assets/Coding_exercise-6.PNG)<n><n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: 600<n><n>Input: Michael makes birdhouses to sell at craft shows. He charges $22 for each large birdhouse, $16 for each medium birdhouse, and $7 for each small birdhouse. This week, he sold 2 large birdhouses, 2 medium birdhouses, and 3 small birdhouses. How much money, in dollars, did he make this week?<n>Output: 97<n><n>Input: Nalani had two female dogs that were expecting and after a month gave birth to 10 puppies each. She then sold 3/4 of the puppies after they came of age, each at $200. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. Another box holds half the amount of the first box and 5 ounces less than the third box. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input: A jug needs 40 cups of water to be full. A custodian at Truman Elementary School has to fill water jugs for 200 students, who drink 10 cups of water in a day. How many water jugs will the custodian fill with cups of water to provide the students with all the water they need in a day?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input:A person lived in my what? Choices:  A: demonstration B: conference C: building D: garage E: mouth<n>Output:		1<n><n># My Answer<n><n>I have solved this problem using BFS <n>``` python<n><n>from datetime import datetime<n>import queue<n><n># Dummy node<n>class Graph:<n>    def add_edge(self, node, child, cost):<n>        self.child[node].add(child)<n>        self.cost[node][child] = cost<n><n># This queue is used to maintain the order of operation<n>queue = queue.Queue()<n>start_time = datetime.now()<n># To be done<n>print("Starting")<n>print(start_time)<n><n># this holds the parent node<n>parent = []<n><n># adding the edges of the graph<n>q = Graph()<n>q.add_edge(i, j, 15)<n>q.add_edges([i, j], [1, 2], 3)<n>q.add(i, 1, 3)<n>q2 = Graph()<n>q2.add_edges(i, [1, 2])<n>q = Graph() # just for learning<n>q.add_child(i, j, cost)<n><n><n><n># this just holds the distance from each destination<n>dist = dict()<n>dist[start] = 0<n><n>for end in [2, 3]:<n><n>    if end not in dist:<n>        print("Going to {0}".format(end))<n>        parent.append(end)<n>        queue.put(end)<n><n>        while not queue.empty():<n>            # get the next node from the queue<n>            u = queue.get()<n>            parent.remove(u)<n>            # calculate the distance of the nodes that are connected to the destination<n>            if u in q.child:<n>                for v in q.child[u]:<n>                    if v not in [t for t in parent if t!= u]:<n>                        # the distance between them is calculated using BFS<n>                        dist[v] = dist[u] + q.cost[u][v]<n>                        queue.put(v)<n><n>            del parent, q.child, q.cost<n><n><n># print(dist) # just for practice<n>print("Started" + datetime.now() - start_time)<n>```<n>

Caterpillars have 6 legs. Centipedes crawl with one pair of legs, having many pairs of legs. Tarantulas have 8 legs. Lastly, arachids are animals that have 8 legs, but tarantulas are particularly hairy types. <n><n>Input: What does an eagle use to build a nest? Choices: A: branches B: woven grass C: shells D: cement <n>Answer: branches - eagles make their nests near the tops of tall trees which bend under their weight. Therefore, the best material from which to build a nest would be a strong branch or branches with which to brace against the high winds. An eagles nest can hold a family of up to 6 eagles, so multiple branches would be needed to hold any

A custodian at Truman Elementary School has to fill water jugs for 200 students, who drink 10 cups of water in a day. How many water jugs will the custodian fill with cups of water to provide the students with all the water they need in a day?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input:John loved competing because he was very competitive.  He liked being about to divide people into what categories? Choices:  A: winners and losers B: perform better C: might win D: losses E: enemies<n>Output:		C<n><n>Input:John was not very ____ because his car broke down right before the race. Choices: B: agile C: efficient D: flexible E: fit<n>Output: A<n><n>Input:Johnâ€™s best friend _____ of the track to see him race. Choices: A: raced B: was going to have the best time C: had been watching all day D: raced fast E: was going to win<n>Output: C<n>Explanation: They are all verbs, except "had." You can't choose "had" because they already watched all day, so you cannot have "had." They also cannot be "was going to" because that implies they are going to do an action. They are then left with "raced, raced fast, and watched." "Raced fast" is an action, "had been watching" is not an action, and "raced" is an action. You can eliminate "had been watching" because we don't know when the action happens. It could be anytime. "Raced fast all day" is an action, we just don't know the timeframe in which it is done: the whole day, only in the morning, all day only at night, etc. The correct answer is "raced" because they are specifically at the track, and they are not doing the action the whole day. They will do it at multiple times during the day, but it is a specific time and place.<n><n>Input:You should eat carrots because they help you get _____. Choices: A1: good eyesight. B: a better view of the world. C: to see really well, especially at night. D: better eyes in the dark. E: a night view.<n>Output: A<n>Explanation:  Weighting these together, I think the one that would be correct is choice A, because getting good eyesight seems to be a direct result of eating carrots, not the other options.<n><n>Input:When the police officer asked John if he had been eating carrots all day, John _____. Choices:. A: laughed B: answered yes C: said â€œnoâ€ D: refused to talk E: said heâ€™d been eating carroty<n>Output: E<n>Explanation: He might not have eating carroty, he might have been

One of the clients' concerns is that of being able to find and purchase local produce, while reducing travel time and cost as much as possible.<n><n>Using what you know about functions, lists, and dictionaries:<n><n>Create a function that takes three input variables as arguments, x, y, and local. The x and y variables represent the latitude and longitude of a desired pickup location.  The local variable represents a Boolean value indicating whether or not the client wishes to make a locally purchased (in other words, reduce the cost and travel time by picking up produce at a nearby location, rather than having produce delivered.).<n><n>The function returns a list of possible pickup locations. Given a latitude and longitude for a desired pickup location and a Boolean value indicating whether the client would prefer local produce, the function should return a list of possible pickpoints that also meet the specified parameters.<n><n>For example: if a client lives in Austin TX with a latitude and longitude of 30.26, -97.74; and they chose local produce, you might be asked to find them a pickup location at Kroger (11611 Metric Blvd Austin, TX 78758; Lattitude: 30.386608; Longitude: -97.813301).<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>```python<n>def checklist(x,y,local):<n>    distance = abs(zipcodes[-1] - zipcodes[0])<n>    distances = []<n>    for j in zipcodes:<n>        dj = distance(y,x,j,local)<n>        distances.append(dj)<n>    return distances<n>```<n><n>## Extra Credit<n><n>### Problem:Find the largest number in a list?<n><n>Input: `[45, 3.5 - 2, 34, 98]<n>Output: 98<n><n>Input: `[89, 8, 9, 43, 23,

Be sure to clearly state your hypothesis in your lab report and have clearly labelled all graphs and data in your lab report. Answer each question based on analysis of the provided lab data. For every experiment type, you must correctly explain the following for each experiment type: <n><n>### Instructions: <n>1. Type the appropriate values for the dependent variable(s), independent variable(s), and control(s) into the correct fields in the lab report form. <n>  > A few fields will require you to enter multiple cells from your lab data. Choices:  A: sneezing B: fatigue C: house clean D: feeling satisfied E: getting good grades<n>Output:		E<n><n><n>```python<n>def multipleChoices(choices, test) : <n>    temp = {}<n>    for i in range (0,len(choices)):<n>        temp[i] = choices[i].lower()<n>    str(test).replace(' ', '').lower().replace('(', '').replace(')', '').split('|')<n>    for i in str(test).split('|') :<n>        if temp[str(test)[i]] == i : <n>            return i <n>    return -1<n>```<n># Problem 13<n>## Instruction: Write a function that takes a string and a list of words and returns a Boolean value indicating<n>## whether the string is a valid English sentence. Choices:  A: wedding B: tennis C: closet D: left foot E: house<n>Output:		tennis<n><n>### Answer to Q1<n>Total candies = total with equal amount + deficit<n>```<n>66 8 + X = X<n>74 = X = 29<n>```<n><n>### AnswerQ2<n><n>```<n>Time = 45 minutes = 0.75 hours<n>Time = 0.31 hours<n>Total time = 0.71 hours * 2 cents per minute + 0.31 * 25 cents per minute = 7.4 cents per minute * 0.71 * 25 * 0.31 = 0.74 * 0.36 * 255<n>Total = 10<n>```<n><n>## AnswerQ3<n>```<n>d = 8 + 5.5 + 8 hours;<n>d = 16.5,<n>15 * 5.5 = x * 5 = 34<n>d = 34,<n>Solve for x,   x = 5<n>```<n><n>## Q4<n><n>```<n>total = 800 - 600 = 200<n>total = (x * 130 = 20) - 10<n>200 - 20 * 130<n>```<n><n>\# Q5<n>```<n>total = (x + 7) * 40<n>total = (19) * 40,<n>total = X * 40<n>```<n><n>AnswerQ6<n>```<n>x = 1/4 + 1/3<n>x = (3/12);<n>x = 30 / 12 = 2.5<n>sold = 2.5 * 200 = 500<n>```<n>AnswerQ7<n><n>```<n>34 = 4b + 3<n>4b + 3 - 3<n>31 = 4b = 7.75<n>```<n><n>Answer8:<n><n>```<n>Total = a + b<n>Total = 24 + 30,<n>total = 54<n>```<n><n>Answer9<n>Total = (y + t) * 4<n>4 = 4 * (y + t)<n>Total = (y+t0;<n>4 = 16 + t0<n>t

She then sold 3/4 of the puppies after they came of age, each at $200. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. How many percent is this population change?<n>Output: 40<n><n>```python<n># Input all of the input statements above so your code can solve them.<n># Use the solution method in the code to get the answers<n>inputs = [<n>    ('Tapanga and Corey', 'Corey has 29 candies'),<n>    ('New Year\'s Eve', 'Freddy spent 10 dollars'),<n>    ('Monday, Tuesday and F', 'Larsen would work 5 hours'),<n>    ('birdhouses to sell', 'he made 97 dollars'),<n>    ]<n><n><n><n>def solution(input_statement):<n>    """ Answer all of the input statements that are given. """<n>    input(), # Prompt the user<n>    # Read input<n>    split = input_statement.split(' ', 1)<n>    type_of_input = split[0]<n>    input_statement_output = split[1]<n><n>    # Print the question<n>    print(type_of_input),<n><n>    # Run the code<n>    if type_of_input == "Percent Change":<n>        # Convert to percent <n>        input_statement_output= format(int(input_statement_output)/100,'.2')<n>    elif type_of_input=="Amount of Cereal":<n>        # Calculate the total amount<n>        input_statement = input_statement_output.split("box")<n>        boxes = int(input_statement[0])  # Get first box from input statement<n>        amount = input_statement[1]  # Get the amount<n>        boxes = input_statement[0] # Get box number in input statement<n>        amount= input_statement[1].split("ounces")<n>        amount= amount[1] # Get the ounces<n>        total_ounces= boxes*amount<n>    elif type_o_f_input == "Amount of Water":<n>        amount = int(input_statment_output.split("ounces")[1])<n>        amount = int((amount*0.0625).replace(".", ","))<n>        total_cereal = amount*

Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. Another box holds half the amount of the first box and 5 ounces less than the third box. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input: A jug needs 40 cups of water to be full. A custodian at Truman Elementary School has to fill water jugs for 200 students, who drink 10 cups of water in a day. How many water jugs will the custodian fill with cups of water to provide the students with all the water they need in a day?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input:what happens to a company when it is bankrupt? Choices:  A: liquidated B: own resources C: branch out D: commit crime E: game over<n>Output:		E: game over ===========<n><n>><n>Both are similar problems, that is the input and output are same. The difference is in the way the text gets displayed. In Instruction, each of the inputs are on distinct line that's why one can't find any particular line in the text. And the output is also displayed on the same line just after the input.<n><n>But in Expectations the Input is shown on one line separated by newline and the output is also shown in one line.<n><n>If the text get's display on the same line, the input will have the newline character(s) at the and and the output will be shown. As we only see the output.<n><n>Hence we will print it in a separate line. To have the newline character we will use os.linesep.<n><n># -*- coding: utf-8 -*-<n><n>import re<n><n>text = "Expectations are similar to instructions."<n>output = re.findall(r'\\n', text)<n><n>print(text)<n><n>'''<n>Output: Expectations are similar to instruction.s<n>'''<n><n># import the os module<n>import os<n><n># read the expectations file, which contains the input in it and the output to be produced after that<n>with open("input-expectations-answers.txt", "r") as f:<n>    text = f.read()<n><n>print(text.join(os.linesep + "=") + os.linesep, end="")<n># print the output in a line separated by os.linesep to match the output from the question<n>output = re.search(r'===\s+', text).group()<n><n>print(output)<n># print the answer which we read from the file here

Now, **subtract** the 2 first elements of the data list and store the result in a **third** variable.<n><n>Output:<n>```<n>var s1 = 4;<n>var s2 = 3;<n>data = [{s1,<n>    s2,<n>    s3,<n>    s4,<n>    s5}<n>output = 11<n>```<n>Hint:<n>```<n>let s1 = 4<n>let s2 = 3<n>let s3 = s1 - s2<n>let slist = [s1, s2, s3]<n>let output = slist[0]<n>```<n>Examples:<n>```<n>var data = [{1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7}<n>var output = 4<n>var list_a = [{1, 1, 1,1,1, 3}<n>var list_b = [{Math.pow(2, 3),Math.pow(3, 3), 3, Math.pow(4, 3)}<n>var list_c = [{2, 5, 8, 11}<n>var output_c = 8;<n>```<n><n>```<n><n>## [03 - Strings](/questions/data-type-strings/9/15.svelte) <n><n># Instruction: <n>Take the string â€œHello Worldâ€, and split the characters into separate strings.<n>Then take the last three characters and combine them into one string.<n>Finally, take the first two characters and combine them into a second string.<n><n>Output: <n>```<n>function create () {<n>    var a = 'Hello World';<n>    var b = a.split();<n>    var c = a.splice()<n>}<n>```<n>### Hint: <n>```<n>    var string = a.charAt(0) + " " + a.charAt(1);<n>    var string2 = a.charAt(" 3");<n>```<n>## [0

Choices:  A: infect B: reproduce C: mutate D: eat food E: make computer malfunction<n>Output:		 C<n><n><n><n>The correct answer is C.<n><n>```python<n>from collections import Counter<n><n>T = int(input())<n>for _ in range(T):<n>    C = int(input()) # input: Tapanga and has 8 candies more.<n>    E2 = input()<n><n>    # E1: 66 candies<n>    # E2: candies in Tapanga and Corecy<n><n>    # c = 19, Corecy c = 80<n>    # e1<n>    c1 = E1.count('6')<n>    e_1 = "".join([str(C) for _ in range(c1)])<n>    print(e_1)<n>    # e2<n>    c2 = E2.count('0')<n>    print(c2)<n>    e_2 = "".join([ str(C) * c for _ in range(13-c2) ])<n>    print(E2 == e_2)<n><n>    # Output:<n>    # 66 candies in Tapangans 6<n>    19C Coreys<n>    Tapanga's c is 100 Corey c is 80 Output:6<n><n>    # Output2: 12 0s, 2 candy of value 00<n>    Output2:6<n><n>    Output3: <n>         Output3: True<n>```<n><n>

Calculates the percentage of input <n>2. Convert input into perentage <n>3. Returns the percentage or decimal converted for perentage conversion```<n><n>    def f1(x):<n>        per = 100/x<n>        return per<n><n>### f2(list(int)):    <n>```1. Calculates the output <n>2. Multiply to find the output <n>3. Add numbers to find the output```<n>    <n>    def f2(x,y):<n>        res = x*y<n>        return res<n><n>## Question_1<n>Output: 14<n><n>Solution: I first converted decimal to percentage then I found the total quantity using percentage and total value using perentage conversion to integer. Then I found the quantity remaining using percentage to integer conversion and then using multiplication to find the output.<n>## Question_2<n>Output: 11 <n><n>Solution: In this question, I used the conversion formula directly to calculate the total amount and I found the output amount using f2(x). Where x is the total amount, which is in dollars and I used f1(x)(100) to find the commission percentage.<n>## Question_3<n>Output: 17<n><n>Solution: This is a simple subtraction problem.<n>## Question_5<n>Output: 20<n><n>Solution: Here I first converted decimal to perentage and then found the amount sold which is 55% and quantity remaining I find it out using percentage to integer conversion. Then the total amount left over I calculate it using percentage to integer conversion again and finally I used multiplication to find the output amount. <n>## Question_6<n>Output: 1500<n><n>Solution : This is a simple perentage problem but I used the converted into integer using percentage to solve it.<n>## Question_7<n>Output: 13<n><n>Solution: <n>Here I used the formula: P= N x

How many chocolates did he eat in total?<n>Output: B<n><n>```<n>Answers (CACHE.java)<n>int cACHE=-1;<n><n>public static void fillCache(){<n>    cACHE=1000;<n>}<n><n>public static int answer(int q_id,String answer,String[] options){<n>    //1.68M<n>    Integer i=cACHE;<n>    <n>    char[] optionChar=new char[options.length];<n>    Scanner sc=new Scanner(System.in);<n>    String user_answer=sc.next();<n>    for(int i=0;i<options.length;++i){<n>        optionChar[i]=options[i].charAt(0);<n>        if(options[i].char At(i)=='A'&&options[i].charAT(i+1)=='S'&&options[i+1].charat(i)=='P'){<n>            optionChar[i]='.';<n>        }<n>    }<n><n>    if(user_answer.equals(answer)){<n>        cACHE=(i+1)%1000;       <n>        return Integer.valueOf(answer);     <n>    }<n>    for(int j=0;j<options.length;j++){<n>        if(user_answer==options[j].substring(1,options[j].length())){<n>            System.out.println("Answer is"+optionChar[j]+answer);<n>            return Integer.valueOf(optionChar[j]); <n>        }     <n>    }<n>      <n><n>    return Integer.valueOf(user_answer);       <n>    }<n>```<n>

How much money, in dollars, did he make this week?<n>Output: 97<n><n>Input: Nalani had two female dogs that were expecting and after a month gave birth to 10 puppies each. She then sold 3/4 of the puppies after they came of age, each at $200. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. Another box holds half the amount of the first box and 5 ounces less than the third box. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input: A jug needs 40 cups of water to be full. A custodian at Truman Elementary School has to fill water jugs for 200 students, who drink 10 cups of water in a day. How many water jugs will the custodian fill with cups of water to provide the students with all the water they need in a day?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input:James was looking for a place to buy bitcoins.  He searched and found a large menu of what? Choices:  A: advertisement B: news C: bar D: cafe E: internet sites<n>Output:		<n><n><n>#### Tips:<n><n>- You can use the String class from Python to store the user's input as strings. This will ensure that the input is stored as a proper sequence of characters, and not as a number or any other type of data.<n>- Always try to limit the length of the user's input to a reasonable length. This will help to keep the program within a reasonable timeframe and reduce the chance of runtime errors due to an overflowing stack or heap.<n>- Using `raw_input()` is more suitable for accepting user input in Python because it accepts input as a string rather than as a number or any binary data type. Raw input is generally safer than using a variable to store the input when working with user input in Python programs. However, it would still be better to perform proper validation and sanitization of the input.<n>- Using `print()` or `print()` can make the program more engaging and interactive. It will also make the process interactive.<n>- Using `if`-`elif` statements is a good choice when there is a single right answer and you want to minimize the number of checks. This is because it will reduce the number of branches that the program needs to check against. However, this can have the downside of increasing the cognitive load on the user.<n>- Try to use the `else` branch when you have multiple correct solutions, this can increase the cognitive load and make the program more difficult to understand. In some cases, it can be better to just have a single `if` statement that returns the answer. It will also provide the user with more structure to follow.<n><n>

Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: 600<n><n>Input: Michael makes birdhouses to sell at craft shows. He charges $22 for each large birdhouse, $16 for each medium birdhouse, and $7 for each small birdhouse. This week, he sold 2 large birdhouses, 2 medium birdhouses, and 3 small birdhouses. How much money, in dollars, did he make this week?<n>Output: 97<n><n>Input: Nalani had two female dogs that were expecting and after a month gave birth to 10 puppies each. She then sold 3/4 of the puppies after they came of age, each at $200. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. Another box holds half the amount of the first box and 5 ounces less than the third box. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input: A jug needs 40 cups of water to be full. A custodian at Truman Elementary School has to fill water jugs for 200 students, who drink 10 cups of water in a day. How many water jugs will the custodian fill with cups of water to provide the students with all the water they need in a day?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input:He had been doing favors for everybody at work, it was frustrating not getting any what for it? Choices:  A: let down B: respect C: illness D: satisfaction E: gratitude<n>Output:		C: illness<n><n>```<n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He sold 60 on Monday, 10 on Tuesday, 20 on Wednesday, 44 on Thursday and 66 on Friday. How many books were not sold?<n>Output: 600<n><n>Input: Michael makes birdhouses to sell at craft shows. He charges $22 for each large birdhouse, $16 for each medium birdhouse, and $7 for each small birdhouse. This week, he sold 2 large birdhouses, 2 medium birdhouses, and 3 small birdhouses. How much money, in dollars, did he make this week?<n>Output: 97<n><n>Input: Nalani had two female dogs that were expecting and after a month gave birth to 10 puppies each. She then sold 3/4 of the puppies after they came of age, each at $200. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. Another box holds half the amount of the first box and 5 ounces less than the third box. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input: A jug needs 40 cups of water to be full. A custodian at Truman Elementary School has to fill water jugs for 200 students, who drink 10 cups of water in a day. How many water jugs will the custodian fill with cups of water to provide the students with all the water they need in a day?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input:The family was playing cards, what would be a reason for this? Choices:  A: amusement B: losing money C: charmed D: having fun E: win money<n>Output:		B<n><n>```Output Explanation: B is a reason for card games. It is not for amusement (A) because its purpose is not to be amused. It is not for losing money (C) because playing cards is a game where you bet with money. It is not to be charmed (D) and it is not for having fun (E) as it is not like going to the park for example.<n>```

How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input: A jug needs 40 cups of water to be full. Where might it be? Choices:  A: new york B: big city C: town D: idaho E: shopping mall<n>Output:		d<n><n>Input:This is the car that they drove.  Which word might work to replace car? Choices:  vehicle mode transportation automobile ride<n>Output: c<n><n>Input:This restaurant is owned by my family.  Which word might replace owned? Choices:  controlled belonged to operated purchased managed<n>Output: c<n>    """<n><n>    def load_data():<n>        """<n>        This method loads and returns the data that'll be used while testing the questions<n><n>        :return: A dictionary containing three keys 'instruction', 'option', and 'answer' which contains the data representing the instruction, the option list, and the answer list<n>        respectively<n>        """<n>        instruction = '### Instruction:Answer the Following Multiple Choice Question.\n\n'<n>        options = ['### Options:\n' + o + '####\n\n####' for o in option_choices]<n>        answer = '### Answer\n' + answer_choices[-1][0] + '\n'<n>        return {'instruction': instruction, 'options': '\n'.join(options), 'answer': answer}<n><n>    test_data = load_data()<n><n>    def test_questions_and_answer(self, *test_cases):<n>        """<n>        Test that the function is working by checking whether the questions asked and the answers received are same as those in load_data<n><n>        :param test_cases: an iterable of tuples<n>        :param test: list of questions and corresponding answers<n>        :param test2: list of questions and correct answers<n>        """<n>        options = set()<n>        question_answers = []<n><n>        for test_pair in test_cases:<n>            _options, _instruction, _answer, _right_answer = test_pair<n>            options.update([o.strip() for o in _options.split('\n')])<n><n>            question_answers.append([q.strip() for q in _instruction.split('\n')] +<n>                                    ['<BR>' + l.strip() for l in _answer.split('\n')][0].split('####'))<n>        options = sorted(options)<n>        answer_dict = {q.strip().split(' ')[0].lower(): a for q, a in zip(question_answers

Where has he been shopping? A. hardware store B. building materials store C. antique store.'<n><n>If you had to choose the correct answer for this question, would you find the answers easily?<n><n>**Hint:** In order to find the correct answer, try to determine the reason why an article asked the question at all. Try to understand what was the point of the question, where did the person shop, and the article wanted the reader to find out because the person bought a table and a bed. Therefore, the correct answer is 'B'.<n><n>In question a) the person did not mention that the candies of Tapanga and Core are different, so, when you find the common denominator, the denominator would be 66 and the numerator would be 9, giving you the answer 29.<n>The correct answer is 29<n><n>In question b) The information you receive from the question is a few facts about an international phone call and what the call cost. Knowing that the call came from Freddy, to dad and then to brother, and the information that the call totaled one dollar, you can easily determine how many phone calls were made that would result in a costs of one dollar. All the information you have is this table. <n>![alt text](https://i.imgur.com/8qeQh93.png "phone charge"). All you have to do is go from the beginning till you encounter a dollar.<n>``` 5 calls, 45 minutes<n>31 minutes <n>31 minutes 50 cents = 5 calls<n>  2 minutes <n>6 minutes 1 <n>----------------------------------       1 dollar```<n>So, the correct answer would be 'choice 5' because there are 5 phone calls in total. You have to count them till you reach a dollar in total. Once you reach a dollar, you stop and consider the option that would give you the greatest answer. Therefore, the value of the answer would be 'choice one'.

House is the location of the bedroom along with the other  places mentioned so it canâ€™t be the correct choice.<n><n>Input:How many quarters would you save up if you collected 8 quarters each day for 6 days?<n>Output: $1.44<n>  Explanation:[8 x (6*4)] + [8*(6-1)] = 8 x 12 + 48 =12.<n>  *Since the number of quarters you have each day is even, we add two quarters to each day. (9,10,11,12)<n>  *When you count the amount you have all together, you see that you have 60 coins, so now you have to double it to get a dollar. The amount of money you will have is 1.20. This is the answer. The best way to find the answer is 1.44 + 10 more than 1.20 = 1.44<n><n>Input:How long is 7 and 1/3 feet?<n>Output: 8.75<n>  Solution: 7 and 1 /3 feet is equivalent to 8 and 2/3 feet. This is because you added 1 and 1/3 to 7.<n>  *We have to convert feet to inches.<n>  *Take the foot (12 inches) and multiply it by 2 and a third.<n>  *Then, you get 25.2 inches. So now you are done with the conversion.<n>  *Now we can convert 8 feet and 2/3 of 12 inches to 1 inch in order to get 4 and 1/3.<n>  *So now you have 25.2 + 4.1 = 29.3.<n>  *Now you can convert all the inches into feet by taking the decimal place before the comma (.) and dividing it by

How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input: A jug needs 40 cups of water to be full. Tapanga and Core<n>y have 66 + 8 = 74 candies in total, so Core<n>y must have 74 - 8 = 66 candies.<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. Choices:  A: make noise B: band C: museum D: concert hall E: rubber band<n>Output:		D<n><n>Input:A man goes to work in the morning and returns home in the afternoon. Which expression will cause the computer to do the same action repeatedly and stop<n>Output:<n><n>[Code]<n><n>Input: 100011110100101110110010*9 (Given as a string)<n>Output:<n>```c<n>#include <stdio.h><n>#include <stdlib.h><n><n>//Write your code here.<n><n>int sum;<n>int check = 1;<n>int array[50], number, length;<n>void function(int);<n><n>int main(void) {<n>  int i;<n><n>  do {<n>    printf( "Enter a number (press <enter> to submit)\n");<n>    scanf("%d", &number);<n>    if (number == 9) {<n>      break; //This is a break statement that tells the compiler to stop the loop.<n>    }<n>    function(number); //This is a function we will be using.<n>  } while (1);<n>}<n><n>void function(int a) {<n>  int temp = 0;<n><n>  for (i = 0; i < 10; i++) {<n>    temp = a % 10; //This will produce a remainder<n>    a = a / 10; //Division<n>    a = a + temp; //Addition<n>    array[i] = a; //This will store 0 in array<n>  }<n><n>  length = i; //This is where we will store the length of the<n>  for (i=0;i<length;i++)<n>    if (array[i]!= 0) {<n>      sum = 0;<n>      check = 1; //This is how we stop the loop.<n>      while (check == 1) {<n>        if (array[i+1] == 0) {<n>          sum += array[i];<n>          check = 0;<n>        } else {<n>          sum += sum;<n>          check = 1; }<n>      } }<n>}<n>```

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. It didn't matter.   He didn't heave anything to put it on, and he lacked the what to balance it? Choices:  A: tenacity B: hands C: coaster D: skill E: breaking<n>Output:		D<n><n>Input:<n><n>For each day, 4 hours were spent outside, with 3 hours spent in school.  After doing errands together, 3 more hours were spent outside.  How many hours were spent inside over the school's 4-day week?<n>Choices:<n><n><n> 48 more hours than outside<n>1 hour less than outside<n>72 fewer hours than outside<n>24 hours less than outside<n><n>Output:<n><n>C<n><n>Input:<n>I want to give my friends the best birthday party but don't know where to start.  I need to buy a cake but I'm not sure how many people will be there.   If I plan a birthday party of 10, I make sure I have enough cake for all my friends.  Then if more people show up, I can always add a bigger cake.  What percent should I add to the cake for every 10 people?<n><n>Choices:<n>5%<n>10%<n>11.11%<n><n>Output:<n>E<n><n><n>The question asks us to round 0.111111... to 1 significant Figure.<n><n>0.111 is represented in a scientific notation as 1 Ã— 10^-1.  1 is the mantissa or significand, and the exponent is 1x10^-1.<n>0.11 = a Ã— 10^x<n>1 is the most significant digit we have, so it is what will remain in our significant figure.   We remove the decimal (remainder to the nearest integer is 0) and move the decimal point 1 position to the left.   Now, we have 1 x 10^0 in our form.  We get rid of the 1, and we get 0.01 x 10^-1 = 0.00111....    <n><n>So the rounding value is 0.1 significant digit, or 0.0<n><n>Input: 3x + 5 = 13<n><n>Output:<n>x = 2<n><n>We can solve it using the linear equations method.<n>We multiply the first equation with x and subtract it in the next equation:<n>3x + (5-3x) = 13<n>(3x + 2) = 13

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. Then he calls his brother, who lives on the other side of the world, and they talk for 31 minutes. Local calls cost 5 cents a minute, while international calls cost 25 cents a minute. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. He worked 5.5 hours on both Wednesday and Thursday. How many hours would Lawrence work each day if he worked the same number of hours each day?<n>Output: 5<n><n>Input: Ali had a stock of 800 books in his Room. He charges $22 for each large birdhouse, $16 for each medium birdhouse, and $7 for each small birdhouse. This week, he sold 2 large birdhouses, 2 medium birdhouses, and 3 small birdhouses. How much money, in dollars, did he make this week?<n>Output: 97<n><n>Input: Nalani had two female dogs that were expecting and after a month gave birth to 10 puppies each. She then sold 3/4 of the puppies after they came of age, each at $200. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. Another box holds half the amount of the first box and 5 ounces less than the third box. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input: A jug needs 40 cups of water to be full.
